		     <h3></h3>
		     <p>Bitcoin was invented as a peer-to-peer system for online payments that does not require a trusted central authority. </p>
		     <p> Since anything digital can be copied over and over again, the hard part about implementing a digital payment system is making sure that nobody spends the same money more than once. Traditionally, this is done by having a trusted central authority (like PayPal or Visa) that verifies all of the transactions. The core innovation that makes Bitcoin special is that it uses consensus in a massive peer-to-peer network to verify transactions. Whoever solves a really difficult and time consuming math problem gets to decide which transactions are verified. This person, called a miner, also gets a 12.5 BTC reward for using his computer power to help secure the system. This results in a system where payments are non-reversible, accounts cannot be frozen, and transaction fees are much lower.</p>
